Cardiovascular disease in patients with hemophilia.

Tuinenburg A(1), Mauser-Bunschoten EP, Verhaar MC, Biesma DH, Schutgens RE.

Author information:
(1)Van Creveldkliniek/Department of Haematology, University Medical Center 
Utrecht, The Netherlands. a.tuinenburg-2@umcutrecht.nl

Mortality due to ischemic heart disease in hemophilia patients is lower as 
compared to the general male population. Differences in the prevalence of 
cardiovascular risk factors cannot explain this finding. The hypocoagulable 
state of hemophilia patients might have a protective effect on thrombus 
formation, which precipitates infarction. It remains unclear whether the 
deficiency of coagulation factor VIII or IX exerts a protective effect on the 
development of atherosclerosis. Despite the relative protection against 
cardiovascular events, the incidence of ischemic cardiovascular disease in 
hemophilia patients is increasing, because life expectancy of these patients now 
approaches that of the general population. This review focuses on what is 
currently known about cardiovascular risk factors, atherosclerosis, arterial 
thrombosis and ischemic cardiovascular disease in hemophilia patients.

